## Conversation
Task: make the gql/graphql-core import lazy so `import weave` stops eagerly
loading a GraphQL client it almost never uses. The task named two files
(weave/trace_server/errors.py and weave/compat/wandb/wandb_thin/internal_api.py)
and expected `import weave` to load 0 graphql modules afterward, with a
subprocess regression test. Instructions: make ONLY this change, commit
locally with git notes, do NOT push / open a PR.

## Actions
- Measured baseline: `import weave` loaded 21 gql + 125 graphql modules.
- Traced module-level gql/graphql import sites with an __import__ hook. Found
  THREE, not two:
    1. weave/trace_server/errors.py:8   (named)
    2. weave/compat/wandb/wandb_thin/internal_api.py:10-11 (named)
    3. weave/wandb_interface/project_creator.py:10  (NOT named by the task)
- Confirmed all three are on the bare `import weave` path (weave.trace.weave_init
  -> weave.compat.wandb -> internal_api; remote_http_trace_server ->
  project_creator; weave_client -> errors).
- errors.py: removed the module-level `from gql.transport.exceptions import ...`.
  Added a deferred import inside ErrorRegistry._setup_common_errors (mirrors the
  existing ClickHouse deferral 6 lines below). TransportServerError is ALSO used
  in _get_transport_server_error_status_code (runtime isinstance -> local import)
  and _get_transport_server_error_message (annotation -> string annotation +
  `if TYPE_CHECKING: from gql.transport.exceptions import TransportServerError`).
- internal_api.py: this file uses gql.gql(...) at CLASS-BODY scope (11 query
  constants that execute at import) and graphql.DocumentNode in annotations, so
  the task's 'just move the import' does not work. Refactor: `from __future__
  import annotations`; converted the 11 `X = gql.gql("...")` class attrs to plain
  parenthesized string literals; added a module-level `@functools.cache
  _compile_query(str) -> GraphQLRequest` that imports gql lazily; the two query()
  methods now compile str->request via `_compile_query(q) if isinstance(q, str)
  else q` and accept `str | GraphQLRequest`; the 8 methods with
  `except gql.transport.exceptions.TransportQueryError` got a local `import gql`.
- project_creator.py: moved the 4-name transport-exceptions import into the two
  predicates that use them (_is_retryable_project_exception, _is_permission_denied).
- Added tests/trace/test_import.py::test_import_weave_does_not_load_graphql - a
  subprocess check (independent of suite import order) asserting no gql/graphql
  modules in sys.modules after `import weave`.

## Errors & mistakes
- First `uv sync` picked Python 3.14 and failed building tiktoken (PyO3 max 3.13).
  Fixed by `uv venv --python 3.12` + `uv sync --group test --python 3.12`.
- Initially annotated `_compile_query`/query() with graphql.DocumentNode. WRONG:
  in gql 4.0 `gql.gql()` returns gql.GraphQLRequest (NOT a DocumentNode; isinstance
  is False) and SyncClientSession.execute takes a GraphQLRequest. Switched all
  annotations to `GraphQLRequest` (imported under TYPE_CHECKING from gql).

## Dead ends
- Considered lazy-loading internal_api via PEP 562 __getattr__ in the compat
  __init__ files instead of refactoring internal_api internals. Rejected: it
  cascades (project_creator imports wandb_logger eagerly; wandb_thin.__init__
  eagerly imports Api/ApiAsync) and adds import-system magic. The leaf-file
  deferral is more predictable.
- Considered `except _lazy_getter() as e:` to avoid 8 local `import gql`.
  Rejected as too clever (clarity over cleverness).

## Hints & warnings
- IT IS ALL-OR-NOTHING. gql is imported once and cached, so `import weave` loads
  all 125 graphql modules if ANY of the three sites remains. Fixing only two of
  the three yields ZERO measurable improvement. This is why project_creator.py
  (unnamed by the task) HAD to be fixed too.
- mypy: repo runs mypy repo-wide via pre-commit (mirrors-mypy) with
  additional_dependencies that do NOT include gql/graphql/aiohttp, so with
  ignore_missing_imports=true those are Any in CI -> the file is mypy-clean there.
  Locally (gql/graphql are py.typed and installed) mypy showed the ORIGINAL file
  had 14 errors and mine has 2. Both remaining errors are PRE-EXISTING and
  unrelated to this change: errors.py `register(formatter=Callable[[TransportServerError],...])`
  contravariance, and internal_api.py `await transport.session.close()` on
  Optional[ClientSession]. Left them (out of scope). My change actually removed
  12 latent local mypy errors (GraphQLRequest-vs-DocumentNode arg-type).
- query() intentionally accepts `str | GraphQLRequest`: internal callers pass the
  string constants; tests/utils/test_ssl_verification.py passes a pre-compiled
  `gql.gql(...)` (a GraphQLRequest). The isinstance guard handles both. Do not
  narrow to `str` only.
- `import gql` (bare) DOES expose gql.transport.exceptions.* (gql's __init__
  imports the client which imports transports) - verified - so the local
  `import gql` in the except-methods reproduces the original behavior exactly.
- ruff (uvx ruff) flagged PLW1510 (subprocess.run without check) - added
  check=False (we assert on returncode ourselves).

